The paper deals with the arrangement of lines in the plane and the complexity of the zone of a circle in this arrangement. This falls under computational geometry (cs.CG) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also uses geometric arguments to prove its results, which suggests that it may also be relevant to computational topology (cs.GT). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of Hart-Sharir sequences, which are related to pseudolines and arrangements of pseudolines, indicating a possible connection to combinatorial algorithms (cs.DS) and systems and control (cs.SY).
